Preheat the #oven to 240°C/220°C fan/gas mark 9.

Chop the @baby potatoes{500%grams} into 2cm chunks.

Pop onto a large (lined) #baking tray{}.

Drizzle with @oil{to taste}, season with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste} then toss to coat. Spread out in a single layer.

When the #oven is hot, bake on the top shelf until golden, ~{25-30%minutes}. Turn the tray halfway through.

> TIP: Use two baking trays if necessary.

Trim and thinly slice the @scallions{2}.

Mix together with the @aioli{1%sachet}.

Season to taste with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste} then set aside.

In a large #bowl, combine the @Worcester sauce{1%sachet} and @breadcrumbs{1%pack}.

Add half the @mustard{1/2%sachet}, 2 tsp @water{to taste} and @salt{1/4%tsp} (double all for 4p).

Add the @Irish beef mince{240%grams}, season with @pepper{} and mix everything together by hand.

Roll into evenly-sized balls, then shape into 1cm thick burgers—one per person.

> IMPORTANT: Wash hands and equipment after handling raw mince.

> TIP: The burgers will shrink a little during cooking.

Return the pan to medium-high heat with a drizzle of @oil{to taste}.

Once hot, fry the burgers until browned on the outside and cooked through, ~{10-12%minutes}. Turn every ~{2-3%minutes}, adjusting the heat if necessary.

Once cooked, remove the #pan from the heat.

> IMPORTANT: Burgers are cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Place some @grated cheese{50%grams} on top of each burger.

Cover the #pan and set aside (off the heat) until the cheese melts, ~{3-4%minutes}.

While the burgers cook, separate the @brioche buns{2}.

Pop into the #oven to warm through, ~{2-3%minutes}.

> TIP: Keep an eye on them so they don't burn!

To assemble the burgers, spread some scallion aioli and @Ballymaloe tomato relish{1%pot} over each base bun.

Top with the cheesy beef burger.

Sandwich closed with the top bun.

Serve with potatoes alongside.